project.title: Example project - International Patient Summary
project.description:
Based on:
https://ckm.openehr.org/ckm/templates/1013.26.376

This example project is loosely based on existing openEHR templates. It is provided for illustrative and educational purposes only. The content does not claim any copyright ownership over the original openEHR templates or materials. This example may be incomplete, simplified, or adapted, and should not be considered an authoritative or comprehensive representation of the original template. For official and complete versions, please refer to the original openEHR resources.
project.author: Martin A. Koch

elements.name: Medication item
elements.description: An individual entry representing a specific medication in the system or list.

elements.name: Name
elements.description: The official or generic name of the medication.

elements.name: Form
elements.description: The physical form in which the medication is supplied (e.g., tablet, capsule, liquid).

elements.name: Category
elements.description: The classification or group to which the medication belongs (e.g., antibiotic, analgesic).

elements.name: Strength
elements.description: The amount of active ingredient per unit of medication (e.g., 500 mg).

elements.name: Strength denominator
elements.description: The denominator used when expressing strength as a ratio (e.g., per 5 mL).

elements.name: Concentration
elements.description: The amount of active ingredient per volume or mass (e.g., 10 mg/mL).

elements.name: Manufacturer
elements.description: The company or entity that produces the medication.

elements.name: Batch
elements.description: The batch or lot number assigned by the manufacturer for quality control and tracking.

elements.name: Expiry date
elements.description: The date after which the medication should not be used.

elements.name: Amount
elements.description: The total quantity of medication provided or prescribed.

elements.name: Alternate amount
elements.description: An alternative quantity measurement for the medication (e.g., number of doses).

elements.name: Role
elements.description: The intended use or function of the medication in treatment (e.g., primary, adjunct).

elements.name: Description
elements.description: A brief summary or explanation of the medication, including its purpose and key details.

elements.name: Order ID
elements.description: A unique identifier for the medication order or prescription.

elements.name: Dose amount
elements.description: The quantity of medication to be administered in a single dose.

elements.name: Formula
elements.description: The calculation or expression used to determine the dose (e.g., mg/kg).

elements.name: Dose description
elements.description: Additional details or notes about the dose.

elements.name: Interval
elements.description: The time period between doses (e.g., every 8 hours).

elements.name: Specific time
elements.description: The exact time(s) when the medication should be administered (e.g., 08:00, 20:00).

elements.name: Timing description
elements.description: Additional explanation or notes about the timing of administration.

elements.name: Exact timing critical?
elements.description: Indicates whether precise timing is essential for the medicationâ€™s effectiveness (Yes/No).

elements.name: As required
elements.description: Indicates if the medication should be given only when needed (PRN).

elements.name: As required criterion
elements.description: The specific condition or reason for administering the medication as needed.

elements.name: Event
elements.description: A specific occurrence or trigger for medication administration (e.g., before meals, after surgery).

elements.name: Event time offset
elements.description: The time difference relative to an event when the medication should be given (e.g., 30 min before).

elements.name: On-off cycle ON
elements.description: The duration or period when the medication is actively being administered in a cyclic regimen.

elements.name: On-off cycle OFF
elements.description: The duration or period when the medication is not administered in a cyclic regimen.

elements.name: Repetitions
elements.description: The number of times a dosing schedule or cycle should be repeated.

elements.name: Route
elements.description: The method or path by which the medication is administered (e.g., oral, intravenous).

elements.name: Body site
elements.description: The specific location on the body where the medication is to be administered (e.g., left arm).
